# Verify before commit — no guessing allowed

Every claim of "done", "works", or "fixed" MUST be backed by a reproducible
command. Vibes / overlays / "should work" are not evidence.

## 1. Build gate (mandatory)

```powershell
npm run build   # must exit 0; fix all TS / import errors before staging
```

## 2. Browser walkthrough — log discipline

When using `cursor-ide-browser` MCP or running `npm run dev`:

1. After **every** navigation or action, call `browser_console_messages` and
   read the dev server terminal file. Do **not** rely on the red issues badge
   alone.
2. Next.js 16 records every browser console message and server log entry to
   `.next/dev/logs/next-development.log` as JSON-per-line. This file is the
   **single source of truth** for "did the page error" — the floating dev
   tools badge only counts the last few. Before declaring a test pass:

   ```powershell
   # MANDATORY end-of-test check — analyses the dev log, filters known
   # extension noise (data-cursor-ref, bis_skin_checked, cz-shortcut-listen)
   # and prints any real ERROR / WARN that needs attention. Exit code 1 if
   # any real ERROR remains.
   node scripts/check-dev-errors.mjs
   ```

   If the script lists any real ERROR (e.g. `TypeError`, `Base UI: ...`,
   `Cannot read properties of`, real hydration diff), fix it before
   committing. Do **not** dismiss warnings as "unrelated" — at minimum
   investigate the file:line shown in the entry.

3. For any hydration / SSR warning, **never** assume "MCP injection" or
   "browser extension". Prove it with the SSR probe:

   ```powershell
   # exits 0 if the marker is NOT in server HTML (safe to ignore),
   # exits 1 if it IS (real SSR/CSR mismatch — must fix)
   node scripts/probe-ssr.mjs http://localhost:3000/<path>
   # Or check a specific marker:
   node scripts/probe-ssr.mjs http://localhost:3000/<path> some-attr-name
   ```

   Already-known client-side injections that this project tolerates:
   - `data-cursor-ref` (cursor-ide-browser MCP)
   - `bis_skin_checked` (Bitdefender browser extension)
   - `cz-shortcut-listen` (ColorZilla browser extension)

   Anything else showing up in a `-` diff line of a hydration mismatch
   message is a **real bug** — fix it.

4. PowerShell ad-hoc greps (Windows shell — `rg` is not installed):

   ```powershell
   # Count ERROR / WARN entries
   (Select-String -Path .next\dev\logs\next-development.log -Pattern '"level":"ERROR"').Count

   # Tail last N entries in human form
   Get-Content .next\dev\logs\next-development.log -Tail 40 |
     ForEach-Object { (ConvertFrom-Json $_).message } |
     Select-Object -First 40
   ```

## 3. Migration verification

A migration file existing is NOT proof it ran. After `npm run db:migrate`:

```powershell
node scripts/apply-migrations.mjs --status   # all rows ✓ applied
node scripts/verify-schema.mjs               # actual columns/enums match expected
npm run db:types                             # regenerate TS types
```

If the migration adds a table / column / enum used by code, write or extend
`scripts/verify-schema.mjs` to assert it exists in the live DB.

## 4. End-to-end smoke for cross-cutting changes

For changes that touch server actions + DB + UI (e.g. order state, payments,
auth flow):

- A passing `npm run build` is necessary but **not sufficient**.
- Write or update a `scripts/smoke-*.mjs` that mutates real rows through the
  same code paths and asserts the resulting DB state. Walk the full happy
  path: form submit → server action → DB row → admin verify → terminal state.
- Run with `--cleanup` when possible to keep the DB tidy.

## 5. Forbidden phrases without evidence

- "should work" / "looks fine" / "probably fine"
- "this is unrelated to my change"
- "the warning is just a [tool] artifact"

For each of the above, attach the command output that proves it. If you
cannot prove it, treat it as a real bug and investigate.
